BACKGROUND:  This update addresses program and project milestones and provides an overview of the current program.  Propositions S and Z, general obligation bond measures to improve every school in the district, were approved by the voters on November 4, 2008 and November 6, 2012.  On May 14, 2013, the board approved the Proposition Z Two-Year Project Plan for implementing projects identified in the Bond Project List and included estimated project schedules.  On December 3, 2013, the board approved an updates to the Proposition Z Two Year Project Plan which also incorporated Proposition S projects and schedules.  On June 3, 2014, Proposition S and Proposition Z Project Plan expanded beyond its two year time horizon and has come to be known as the multiple year project plan.  The multiple year project plan has subsequently been updated on December 2, 2014, and June 2, 2015.  In response to board priorities and direction, staff is presenting its latest update to the multiple year project plan for board approval which includes reference to the voter guide for projects.

RECOMMENDATION:  Deny the charter petition to establish City Farming Academy of San Diego (City Farming Academy) as a new charter school.  Staff recommends the board adopt, in support of a denial, the following written factual findings.

 

FINDINGS:

  1. The City Farming Academy petition does not contain the required number of signatures as petitioners are unable to confirm that the version of the petition that teachers and parents received for review is the same version of the petition that was submitted to the district.
  1. The City Farming Academy petition does not contain a reasonably comprehensive description of staff retirement systems.  If approved as written, City Farming Academy would not offer California State Teachers' Retirement System (CalSTRS) or California Public Employees' Retirement System (CalPERS).
  1. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition based on an unrealistically high enrollment projection.
  1. The City Farming Academy petition presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school because the school has an unmanageable academic calendar that includes opening a week before the district and being closed from November 21 to January 2, while planning to be a “school of the district” for special education staffing and service purposes.
  1. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because the school has presented an unrealistic financial and operational plan as the budget does not appear to have reasonable estimates of revenues and expenditures.
  1. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because the budget is not fiscally viable.
  1. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because the cash flow reflects a lack of understanding of receipt of revenues and expenditures.
  1. City Farming Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter because the school is unfamiliar with the content of the petition as it relates to instructional minutes, conflict of interest, bylaws, and governance.
  1. The City Farming Academy charter petition presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school because the school has not completed its due diligence related to housing animals at a public school within the City limits.

FISCAL IMPACT:  None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT:  None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING:  None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE:  Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  The public hearing for the City Farming Academy of San Diego charter petition was held on November 3, 2015. The lead petitioner is Therese FitzRandolph, owner and director of the Learning Convergence at 3505 Camino Del Rio S #138, San Diego, CA 92108.  The Learning Convergence is a company that provides reading and math support for students in a one-on-one setting.

 

City Farming Academy is seeking approval of its charter petition for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021. 

 

City Farming Academy proposes to open with Grades TK-3 in August 2016, and eventually serve Grades K-8. 

 

With regard to facilities, the City Farming Academy charter petition identified the following sites as possible locations for the school:

  1. 5555-5557 University Avenue, San Diego, CA  92105
  2. 3544 Euclid Avenue, San Diego, CA  92105
  3. 2520 Camino Del Rio South, San Diego, CA  92108

On November 10, 2015, City Farming Academy sent an email stating, “We have secured a location at the Kroc Center in the 92115 Rolando Park area.”

 

Education Code section 47605(b) states that the governing board of a school district shall not deny a petition for the establishment of a charter school unless it makes written factual findings, specific to the particular petition, setting forth specific facts to support one or more of the following findings:

  1. The charter school presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school.
  2. The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the petition.
  3. The petition does not contain the number of signatures required in Education Code section 47605(a).
  4. The petition does not contain an affirmation of each of the conditions described in Education Code section 47605(d).
  5. The petition does not contain reasonably comprehensive descriptions of Education Code sections 47605(b)(5)(A)-(P).

FINDINGS:

 

Finding 1: The City Farming Academy petition does not contain the required number of signatures as petitioners are unable to confirm that the version of the petition that teachers and parents received for review is the same version of the petition that was submitted to the district.
 

According to the lead petitioner, parents signed the petition while they were at the City Farmers Nursery, the Hillcrest farmers market, or the City Heights farmers market.  Petitioners stated that the petition was in a binder and was available for parents to review.  It was further stated that a team of five teachers helped write the petition and that the lead petitioner wrote the agriculture section and served as the project manager.  Petitioners indicated that revisions to the petition were made at various times, by various people, including revisions from a law firm.  The parent signatures occurred over a three-month period from June 27, 2015, through September 27, 2015.  Given the three month timeframe of the signature collection, and the fact that revisions were made, it has not been confirmed that the version of the petition that parents viewed is not the version that was submitted to the district.

 

The district is also concerned about the teacher signatures.  Similar to the parent signatures, the teacher signatures were obtained at the City Farmers Nursery.  The teacher signature page has the following statement on it, “We agree to the contents of the attached charter proposal dated August 14, 2015 and will work toward its implementation….”  The charter petition was submitted to the district on October 2, 2015.  Petitioners were unable to confirm that the version of the petition that the teachers signed is the same version that was submitted to the district.

 

Additionally, Education Code section 47605 states that the petition shall be signed by a number of teachers that is equivalent to at least one-half of the number of teachers that the charter school estimates will be employed at the school during its first year of operation.  The school estimates it will employ six teachers during its first year of operation, and six teachers signed the petition.  However, when the district verified their signatures, only one of the teachers was eligible to teach at the school during the first year, or was meaningfully interested in teaching at the school.  Below is a summary of the reasons why all but one of the teachers is ineligible or not meaningfully interested:

  • Teacher is only interested if the school offers STRS
  • Cannot afford to teach at the school because the teacher almost ready to retire
  • Teacher is hoping to be tenured next year with current employer
  • Teacher does not hold the appropriate credential for TK-3
  • Teacher only holds a special education credential (the school has elected to remain with the district for special education during the first year so district staff will provide special education services at the school)

Finding 2: The petition does not contain a reasonably comprehensive description of staff retirement systems.  The petition does not address CalSTRS and CalPERS.  The petition is unclear as to which positions will be covered by federal social security; it only states that “all eligible employees” will participate.  The petition states, “City Farming Academy of San Diego plans to work directly with the San Diego County Office of Education (or another approved benefits administrator) to forward in a timely fashion any required payroll deductions and related data.” The San Diego County Office of Education is not a benefits administrator.  In addition, during the district staff’s signature verification process, a teacher who signed the charter petition indicating a meaningful interest in being employed by the charter school, stated the interest is only there if the school offers CalSTRS.

 

Finding 3: The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition regarding the school’s projected enrollment.  The petition presents an overly optimistic projection, in the district’s judgment and based on historical data, for its first year enrollment.  The petitioners indicated that they plan to enroll 150 students in grades TK/K-3 during the first year of operation.  The table below summarizes the historical data (since the 2010-11 school year) for other district-authorized charter schools that opened with Grades K-3 and compares it with the City Farming Academy’s projections.

Finding 4: The City Farming Academy petition presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school because the school has an unmanageable academic calendar.  The City Farming Academy petition states, on page 102, that the school “shall initially remain, by default, a public school of SDUSD for purposes of special education,” which means the district would be responsible for staffing the charter school in accordance with current collective bargaining agreements.  City Farming Academy is proposing an academic calendar that will create an unmanageable staffing issue.  City Farming Academy intends to start school on August 22, 2015, a full week before the district begins school.  In addition, the charter school intends to be closed for an extended break from November 21, 2016, through January 2, 2017.  This calendar does not align with the district’s traditional or year-round calendars.

 

Finding 5: The City Farming Academy petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because the school has presented an unrealistic financial and operational plan.  The budget does not appear to have reasonable estimates of revenues and expenditures

  • Educational Protection Account (EPA) revenues are included in the budget in fiscal years 2019-20 and 2020-21.  EPA funds generated through Prop. 30 will expire at the end of fiscal year 2018-19.  The budget overestimated EPA revenue by $71,250 in fiscal year 2019-20 and $85,500 in fiscal year  2020-21 for a total of $156,750 over the two fiscal years.
  • The Charter School Facility Grant Program (Senate Bill 740 Program) provides state funds for charter school facilities.  If a charter school is eligible, it is awarded $750 per unit of classroom-based Average Daily Attendance, up to 75 percent of annual facilities rent and lease costs.  The budget overestimated this revenue by $16,875 in fiscal year 2016-17 and by $7,500 in fiscal year 2017-18 for a total of $24,375 over the two fiscal years.
  • City Farming Academy proposed to be in the district SELPA during fiscal year 2016-17.  For fiscal year 2015-16, the district's special education contribution rate per student is $1,613. The budget assumes a special education contribution rate of $1,300 per student resulting in a $46,963 understatement of expenses in fiscal year 2016-17.

Finding 6: The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because the budget is not fiscally viable.  The budget shows a negative $40,000 ending fund balance in the startup year.

 

Finding 7: The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because the cash flow reflects a lack of understanding of receipt of revenues and expenditures.

  • For fiscal year 2015-16, receipt of in lieu of property taxes is shown in October, January, and March through June.  Pursuant to Education Code Section 47635(b), in lieu of property taxes is transferred to charter schools in monthly installments.
  • The petition narrative references receivable sales in the first two years of operation.  Charter Asset Management has committed to $750,000 in financing for fiscal year 2016-17 only (Appendix H).  No evidence has been provided to substantiate the funding in the second year of operation.  No supporting documentation has been provided detailing the fees or rates related to the financing.  Without the financing, City Farming Academy will have negative cash flows in the first two years of operation.

Finding 8: City Farming Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter because the school is unfamiliar with the content of the petition as it relates to instructional minutes, conflict of interest, bylaws, and governance.  On page 80 of the petition, it indicates that students in Grades 1-8 will receive 420 minutes of instructional time on regular days, and 210 minutes on minimum days.  Based on the grade level (Grades 1-3, Grades 4-6 and Grades 7-8) sample schedules included on pages 84-86 of the petition, it appears that the daily instructional minutes have been overestimated.  All of the schedules include a nutrition break of 10 or 15 minutes in the instructional minute calculation; however, nutrition breaks may not be included as part of the instructional minutes.  This results in a daily overestimation of 15-minutes for Grades 1-6, and a daily 10-minute overestimation of minutes for Grades 7-8.  The schedules reflect the minimum instructional minutes required, but there is a concern that the school does not understand what can be included in the instructional minute calculation.

 

The petitioners are demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition regarding the bylaws and conflict of interest code.  Pages 238-254 of the petition contain the school’s bylaws.  The bylaws are in draft form, have not been signed by anyone representing the school, and there is no indication that the bylaws have been approved by the City Farming Academy board of directors.  Similarly, the conflict of interest code on page 255 of the petition is in draft form and there is no indication that it has been approved by the City Farming Academy board of directors.

 

During the capacity interview with the lead petitioner on November 6, 2015, it was stated that the City Farming Academy board of directors has not been appointed for the school.  It is concerning that plans and decisions are being made on behalf of the school but there is no board approving these actions. 

 

Finding 9: The City Farming Academy petition presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school because the school has not completed its due diligence related to animals at a public school within the City limits.  The City Farming Academy petition contains multiple references to animals at the school, specifically chickens (pages 30, 88, and 336) and goats (pages 29-30).  The petition, however, does not provide any information on whether the petitioners have verified that these animals are allowed within the City of San Diego limits and/or if they are allowed at a public school site.  In addition, there is no information provided as to what, if any, restrictions the City of San Diego has on these animals, and further, if there are any restrictions that exist for having them at a public school site, including the specific locations proposed in the petition.  For example, is there a limit to the number of animals, or the size of the animals?

 

District staff has reviewed the attached City Farming Academy of San Diego charter petition and recommends the board adopt the above-identified factual findings in support of a denial.

RECOMMENDATION: Grant Renewal of the Charter and Special Education Agreement for City Heights Preparatory Academy Charter School for five-year terms beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None. 

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  As the charter granting authority, the board has several options with respect to the renewal of City Heights Preparatory Charter School (City Heights Prep):

  1. Grant renewal for a five-year term and serve Grades 6-12, as projected.
  2. Grant renewal for a five-year term and continue serving Grades 6-9. 
  3. Deny renewal and adopt the findings contained within this report.

Staff recommends the board grant the renewal of the charter and special education agreement for City Heights Prep for five-year terms and serve Grades 6-12, as projected. 

 

OVERVIEW

 

On February 1, 2011, the board approved a petition to establish City Heights Prep for a three-year term, from July 1, 2011, to June 30, 2014.  City Heights Prep was approved to serve Grades 6-12, opening with Grade 6 and adding a level in each subsequent year.

 

City Heights Prep decided to delay its 2011-12 opening and began serving students in the 2012-13 academic year. 

 

On December 3, 2013, the board granted City Heights Prep an extension of its charter term from the original three-year period to the full five-year period ending June 30, 2016, which allowed City Heights Prep to generate additional data regarding academic achievement.

 

On November 3, 2015, the district held a public hearing to consider the level of support for the renewal of City Heights Prep. 

 

City Heights Prep is operated by a nonprofit public benefit corporation of the same name.  The school is located on a non-district site at 3770 Altadena Avenue, San Diego, 92105, which falls within the Crawford High cluster. 

 

The educational program at City Heights Prep includes the following:

  • A modified block schedule with an extended school day.
  • Small classes, before school tutoring, after school study hall, and small counseling groups to support student needs.
  • Intersession day camps designed to serve at-risk students, including a Trauma Healing Camp and intensive English language support.

FINDINGS

  1. Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(1) the City Heights Prep charter petition presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the school based on the lack of data demonstrating academic achievement.  This finding is supported by the following information:
  1. Pursuant to Education Code sections 47605(b)(1) and 47607(a)(3)(A), the district has considered increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant the City Heights Prep charter renewal and has determined that City Heights Prep school has not met any of the following criteria in Education Code section 47607(b):
  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school. 
  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years. 
  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.  
  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.  
  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).
  1. The district has reviewed the following information from the California Department of Education:

Assembly Bill (AB) 484 amended California Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 and 2014–15 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  • The most recent API calculation;
  • An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or
  • Alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups.

The decision to use one of the above criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

 

Based on the most recent API calculation of 534 in 2012-13 and lack of data such that an average could not be calculated, City Heights Prep has not demonstrated sufficient increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school.

  1. Pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), City Heights Prep is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program set forth in the charter petition because the projected enrollment  includes a 100 percent retention rate from Grade 9 to Grade 12, which is unrealistic and does not reflect the school’s historical retention rate.  Page 12 of the City Heights Prep charter petition shows an 84 percent historical retention rate; however, page 16 reflects a 100% projected retention rate.

BACKGROUND: Staff recommends the board grant the renewal of the charters and special education agreements for King-Chavez Academy of Excellence (KC Excellence) and King-Chavez Preparatory Academy (KC Prep) for five-year terms beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021. 

 

The public hearing to consider the level of support for KC Excellence and KC Prep was held on November 3, 2015.

 

KC Excellence and KC Prep are two out of the six charter schools operated by the nonprofit public benefit corporation, King-Chavez Academy of Excellence.  Table 1 below summarizes the schools. 

 

TABLE 1: King-Chavez Charter Schools by Grade Levels

KC Excellence is located on a district site at 2850 Logan Avenue (92113) which is located in the San Diego High cluster.  KC Prep is located on a private site located at 500 30th Street (92102) which is located in the San Diego High cluster. 

 

The educational program at KC Excellence and KC Prep include the following:

  • Power Hour – The students work in homogenous groups on literacy skills prescribed by formative assessment data.  During this time, students and teachers are supported by special education staff and well-trained aides.
  • Mindfulness – Students are taught to regulate their emotions and center themselves via techniques such as yoga and meditation.
  • Restorative Justice Practices (Make It Right) – In an effort to eliminate out of school suspensions and to curb the School-to-Prison-Pipeline, the schools have instituted a process to collectively identify and address harms, needs, and obligations, in order to heal and put things as right as possible. 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement if any.

 

Staff has visited KC Excellence and KC Prep annually. The annual site visit includes document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board member(s), teacher(s), administrator(s), financial manager(s), parent(s), and/or student(s). During the annual site visit, as well as throughout the year, the areas of academics, finances, and operations are monitored as part of the district’s oversight duties.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

A charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school. 
  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years. 
  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.  
  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.  
  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).

Assembly Bill (AB) 484 amended Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 and 2014–15 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  1. The most recent API calculation;
  2. An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or
  3. An alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups. 

The decision to use one of these criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

Jorge “Gabe” Collins became the Principal of KC Excellence effective March 1, 2015.  Previously, Mr. Collins served as a Middle School Lead Teacher at the school.

 

Scott Worthing is the Principal of KC Prep effective May 26, 2015.  Previously, Mr. Worthing served as the Principal of King-Chavez Arts Academy and King-Chavez Athletics Academy.

 

KC Excellence and KC Prep are members of the El Dorado County Charter Special Education Local Plan Area (SELPA).  As of December 1, 2014, KC Excellence enrolled 40 students with IEPs, totaling approximately 12.1 percent of the schoolwide population.  As of December 1, 2014, KC Prep enrolled 43 students with IEPs, totaling approximately 12.2 percent of the schoolwide population. 

 

The King-Chavez board is the decision-making body for the six King-Chavez charter schools, including KC Excellence and KC Prep.  Board meetings occur approximately every other month, rotating among each of the campuses, and are held within district boundaries. Generally, meetings are held in the evening at 4:30 p.m. The King-Chavez charters and bylaws allow for a minimum of five and a maximum of seven board members.  The table below summarizes the current board roster.

As described in the KC Excellence charter beginning on page 25 and in the KC Prep charter beginning on page 24, opportunities for parent involvement include the following:

  • The King-Chavez parent groups representing all of six of the charter schools nominate one parent to sit on the charter governing board.  The nominee is selected by a vote of a representative from each King-Chavez parent organization.
     
  • Parents are strongly encouraged to become members of the Parent-Teacher Organization (PTO) which meets monthly.  The PTO provides opportunities for parents and charter employees to communicate about ongoing issues, plan school-wide events, fundraise, and provide classroom support as needed.
     
  • In addition to the PTO, a group of parents have been elected to participate in School Site Council (SSC) and English Language Advisory Committee (ELAC). The SSC focuses on school financials and academics and works alongside administration in the decision-making process of King-Chavez. The ELAC works alongside the principal, staff, and SSC on programs, services, and goals for English Learners. The ELAC also supports the development of each school’s needs assessment, and ways to promote high attendance rates.

BACKGROUND: Old Town Academy opened in 2011, and operates a charter school serving Grades K-8 on a non-district site at 2120 San Diego Avenue, San Diego, 92110, which falls within the San Diego High/Point Loma High clusters.

 

On October 2, 2015, Old Town Academy submitted a renewal petition which reflected the school’s August 2014 merger/sale to Tri Valley Learning Corporation, a Livermore-based Charter Management Organization.  On November 3, 2015, the Board of Education held a public hearing to consider the level of support to renew the charter of Old Town Academy.  The district relayed to Old Town Academy its concerns regarding the governance, finance, and operations as presented in the renewal petition.

 

Old Town Academy subsequently submitted a revised petition to the district on November 23, 2015.  The revised petition does not contemplate the merger with Tri Valley Learning Corporation.  In a special board meeting held on November 24, 2015, the Tri Valley Board voted to rescind the Memorandum of Understanding with Old Town Academy, pending the renewal by San Diego Unified School District.

 

Staff recommends the board grant the request to renew the charter of Old Town Academy and Special Education Agreement for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021, with the following conditions.

 

Condition 1:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that on or before December 11, 2015, Old Town Academy agrees and affirms that it has terminated its merger/sale transaction with Tri Valley Learning Corporation, including rescinding all documents used in the transaction, and that it will not seek a merger and/or sales transaction with Tri Valley Learning Corporation or any other Charter Management Organization during the term of the renewal.

 

Included as part of the merger/sales transaction were the following documents:

  • A Bill of Sale dated July 1, 2015.
  • A Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) between Tri Valley and Old Town Academy.
  • An Asset Purchase Agreement entered into August 2, 2014.
  • An Assignment and Assumption Agreement dated August 2, 2014.

The district is requiring affirmation that all of the above-listed documents used in the transfer of Old Town Academy to Tri Valley Learning Corporation have been rescinded by both the Tri Valley board and the Old Town Academy board.

 

Further, Old Town Academy affirms to the district, as stated by the Old Town Academy board chair, that Old Town will not seek any merger and/or sales transaction with Tri Valley Learning Corporation or any other Charter Management Organization during the term of the renewal. 

 

Condition 2:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that on or before December 11, 2015, Old Town Academy shall provide documentation to the Office of Charter Schools that demonstrates for all employees at Old Town Academy (teachers and other staff), whether they are directly employed by Old Town Academy or fall under a “lease back” employment services agreement, that Old Town Academy is deemed the exclusive public school employer for all employees at Old Town Academy for purposes of the Educational Employment Relations Act.  The following language in the petition should be revised to reflect the above statement.

  • Page 5: “Currently, TVLC is the employer of all employees serving the school. This arrangement allows OTA the opportunity to provide better benefits to the employees. Going forward, those employees shall either revert to direct employment by OTA, which shall be deemed the exclusive public school employer of the employees of Old Town Academy for purposes of the Educational Employment Relations Act, or shall be leased back to OTA pursuant to an employment services agreement wherein OTA shall retain all supervisory authority over the employees.”
  • The new language should read, “For the renewal term, beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021, OTA shall be the employer of all employees serving the school and as such OTA shall be deemed the exclusive public school employer of the employees of OTA for the purposes of the Educational Employment Relations Act.  In the event OTA employees serving OTA are “leased back” to OTA pursuant to an employment services agreement with a third party entity for the purpose of providing better benefits to the employees, this employment services agreement shall explicitly state that OTA shall be deemed the exclusive public school employer of these employees for the purpose of the Educational Employment Relations Act.”

Condition 3:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that on or before December 11, 2015, Old Town Academy shall provide documentation to the Office of Charter Schools that demonstrates the steps taken to change the Agent for Service of Process from Bill Batchelor in Livermore to Jon Centofranchi in San Diego.

 

Condition 4:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that on or before December 11, 2015, Old Town Academy will sign and return the attached special education agreement.

 

Condition 5:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that the following language regarding the SELPA is removed from the petition:

  1. Page 21:  OTA joined a special education local plan area (SELPA) pursuant to Education Code Section 47641(a), and OTA is a member in good standing in the El Dorado County Charter SELPA and, as such, uses this SELPA for its schools.  A change in LEA status or SELPA membership shall not require a material revision of this charter.

Condition 6:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that the following language related to special education be changed in the petition:

  • Page 21:  “However, if the student’s needs as documented on the IEP require a program other than inclusion, the school will work with the El Dorado County Charter SELPA to provide an appropriate placement and services.”
  • The new language, suggested by Old Town Academy, will be revised to, “students will receive all appropriate services from the school.  If the services are not directly available at the school, the principal will work with the El Dorado County Charter SELPA to coordinate the best possible delivery of necessary services to the student at the school.”

Condition 7:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that the bylaws are revised to match the number of board members stated in the petition.

 

On page 61 of the renewal petition, it states that “[t]he OTA board shall have a minimum of five and maximum of 11 members.”  The bylaws state that the number of directors “shall be not less than five (5) or more than fifteen (15)…”  The bylaws should be revised to indicate a minimum of five board members and a maximum of eleven board members.

 

Condition 8:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that a “typographical” error in Element G (means to achieve racial/ethnic balance reflective of district) be removed, as indicated below:

  1. On page 70 of the petition it states, “[t]he development of promotional and information material that appeals to all of the various racial and ethnic groups represented within the boundaries of the San Diego Unified School District: especially Regions C and D (The new charter school will be right on the border of San Diego Unified District’s Region D…)”

Condition 9:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that the Dispute Resolution Procedures in the petition be revised as indicated below:

 

In the event of a dispute between the Charter School and the Authorizer, Charter School staff, employees and Board members of the Charter School and the Authorizer agree to first frame the issue in written format (“dispute statement”) and to refer the issue to the Authorizer Superintendent or designee and Principal of the Charter School.  In the event that the Authorizer Board of Education believes that the dispute relates to an issue that could lead to revocation of the charter in accordance with Education Code Section 47607, the Charter School requests that this shall be noted in the written dispute statement, although it recognizes it cannot legally bind the Authorizer to do so.  However, participation in the dispute resolution procedures outlined in this section shall not be interpreted to impede or act as a pre-requisite to the Authorizer’s ability to proceed with revocation in accordance with Education Code Section 47607.

 

The Principal and Superintendent or designee shall informally meet and confer in a timely fashion to attempt to resolve the dispute, not later than 5 business days at the earliest mutually convenient date from receipt of the dispute statement.  In the event that the informal meeting fails to resolve the dispute, both parties shall identify two Board members from their respective boards two representatives from their respective organizations who shall jointly meet with the Superintendent or designee and the Principal of the Charter School and attempt to resolve the dispute within 15 business days from receipt of the dispute statement.

 

If this joint meeting fails to resolve the dispute, the Superintendent or designee and the Principal shall meet to jointly identify a neutral third party mediator to engage the Parties in a mediation session designed to facilitate resolution of the dispute.  The format of the mediation session shall be developed jointly by the Superintendent or designee and the Principal.  Mediation shall be held within sixty business days of receipt of the dispute statement at the earliest mutually convenient date.  The costs of the mediation shall be split equally between the Authorizer and the Charter School.  The charter school shall be solely responsible for its attorney’s fees, if any, and any other costs or expenses arising from dispute.  If mediation does not resolve the dispute either party may pursue any other remedy available under the law.  All timelines and procedures in this section may be revised upon mutual written agreement of the Authorizer and the Charter School.

 

Condition 10:  Staff recommends the board grant Old Town Academy’s renewal with the condition that on or before December 11, 2015, Old Town Academy submit a more detailed budget to the district.  The budget should reflect a breakdown of revenues and expenditures by object code, more clarification on budget assumptions, and funding rates and calculations used to determine revenues.

 

CONCLUSION

Staff recommends the board grant the renewal of the charter of Old Town Academy for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021, with the above-stated conditions and clarifications.

RECOMMENDATION: Staff recommends the board deny the renewal of the charter of Old Town Academy, a charter school, and adopt the following factual findings.

 

FINDINGS

  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school has presented an unrealistic operational plan by relinquishing governance control of the school to an outside, non-local entity, Tri Valley Learning Corporation (Tri Valley).
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter based on the lack of local parental, staff, and community access to the Tri Valley Learning Corporation Board of Directors, which is located in Northern California, approximately 400 miles away from the school.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school will not be able to fulfill the “local control” components of the Local Control Funding Formula or the Local Control Accountability Plan if all governance and financial decisions are made by an entity based in Northern California.
  1. Old Town Academy presents an unsound educational program based on the school’s failure to appropriately serve its special education student population.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school is unfamiliar with the content of the petition as it relates to enrollment preferences, student fees, corporation status, closure procedures, and number of schools.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school, despite repeated requests and letters from the district, and a resolution passed by the Old Town Academy board in July 2015, continued to authorize Tri Valley to make financial and operational decisions.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because Tri Valley’s past history of involvement with charter schools has been unsuccessful, and a Tri Valley board member’s past history of involvement with charter schools has been unsuccessful.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the former CEO of Tri Valley Learning Corporation, Bill Batchelor, has a concerning history with the intermingling of a private school that is co-located with a charter school under the control of Tri Valley.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school has presented an unrealistic financial plan by relinquishing financial control of the school to Tri Valley, an organization that is reported to have unpaid invoices totaling over $200,000 to a community college.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school has presented a vague and unclear administrative services plan.
  1. Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school has presented a vague and unclear budget and cash flow that is inconsistent, inaccurate, and possibly a misrepresentation.

BACKGROUND: Old Town Academy opened in 2011, and operates a charter school serving Grades K-8 on a non-district site at 2120 San Diego Avenue, San Diego, 92110, which falls within the San Diego High/Point Loma High clusters.  On November 3, 2015, the Board of Education held a public hearing to consider the level of support to renew the charter of Old Town Academy. 

 

Staff recommends the board deny the request to renew the charter of Old Town Academy and adopt the findings specified within this report.

 

Finding 1:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter because the school has presented an unrealistic operational plan by relinquishing governance control of the school to an outside, non-local entity, Tri Valley Learning Corporation (Tri Valley or TVLC).

 

Throughout the renewal petition, there are multiple references to the Old Town Academy Board no longer existing if the renewal is granted.  Page 60 of the renewal petition states that the school will be “governed pursuant to the bylaws adopted by the TVLC board.” 

 

The current Old Town Academy Board will become the “site council” for the school, and will serve in an “advisory capacity” to the Tri Valley board (page 61 of charter renewal petition, emphasis added). 

 

All final decisions related to the finances and governance of the school will be made solely by the Tri Valley board, which also oversees four other charter schools in Northern California. 

 

The Old Town Academy Board is changing from being a decision-making body to an “advisory” role.  This substantially transforms the school into a very different charter and governance structure than what was initially authorized by the district.  The proposed changes alter the school in such a significant way that it appears this should not be a renewal petition, but rather a petition for a new school.

 

The district is also concerned about the fiduciary responsibility that Tri Valley board members will have for Old Town Academy.  The Tri Valley board is currently composed of seven members, including one member who was selected from the Old Town Academy site council.  Four of the current members appear to be either a parent or grandparent of students enrolled in the Livermore-based charter schools operated by Tri Valley.  Page 62 of the renewal petition states that the Tri Valley “Board of Directors…have fiduciary responsibility for the well-being of the organization and the School.”  With the majority of the Tri Valley board members having strong connections to the Livermore charter schools, there is a concern about whether the Tri Valley board would be able to adequately and appropriately carry out its fiduciary responsibilities as they relate to Old Town Academy.

 

A further concern is a limitation set out in Article VII, Section 4(f), of the Tri Valley Amended Bylaws (page 159 of the renewal petition), which states, “[i]n the event a charter authorizer chooses to seat a voting board member, that members voting rights and participation are limited to open session issues related only to the charter school for which they are the chartering authority.”  This creates a Tri Valley board member with limited voting rights, which further confuses the governance structure for Old Town Academy.  If approved as written, a district-appointed member of the charter board would have no say in important closed session items, such as litigation, personnel decisions, student expulsions, collective bargaining, and real estate transactions.

 

Finding 2:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter based on the lack of local parental and staff access to the Tri Valley Board, which is located approximately 400 miles away from Old Town Academy.

 

It is imperative that parents, staff, and community members are able to easily interact with the ultimate decision-makers for a locally authorized public charter school.  The proposed charter renewal would require parents and staff to interact with the Tri Valley board, which is based in Northern California, specifically Livermore.  Below are multiple examples from the charter renewal petition that require parents and staff to interact with the Tri Valley board in Livermore.

  • Page 17 of the charter requires students and their families “to appear and present their case before the TVLC board” in order to appeal Old Town Academy’s decision related to admission and/or enrollment preferences
  • Page 70 of the charter states that all complaints received by Old Town Academy are to be directed to the Tri Valley Board, and the Tri Valley CEO is responsible for investigation, remediation, and follow up.
  • Page 143 of the charter requires employees to contact the Tri Valley board to hear grievances at a regularly scheduled board meeting, which are held in Livermore.
     
  • Page 231 of the charter requires that a student expulsion hearing be done before the Tri Valley board in Livermore, or that the Tri Valley board make a final recommendation for expulsion.

In reviewing the current Tri Valley board meeting schedule it is noted that all meetings for the 2015-16 year are held at the Livermore site.  There is nothing in the renewal petition indicating that Tri Valley board meetings will be held in San Diego.  It is unlikely that any of the meetings would be held in San Diego considering all but one of the current board members live in Northern California.

 

Finding 3:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter because the school will not be able to fulfill the “Local Control” components of the Local Control Funding Formula or the Local Control Accountability Plan if governance, operations, and finance functions are controlled by a Livermore-based corporation.

 

As stated throughout the renewal petition, Old Town Academy will be operated and governed by Tri Valley.  On Page 60, the renewal petition indicates that the only aspects of the school that will remain under the control of the local Old Town Academy site council are the “school’s parent/student handbook, faculty handbook, and other school policies and procedures that are currently or anticipated to become in effect at the school.”  Every other aspect of the governance, finance, and operations will be controlled and decided by Tri Valley.  When the school updates its annual LCAP it will have to be approved by Tri Valley, and any funds mentioned in it will have to be expended based on a budget approved by Tri Valley. 

 

Finding 4:  The Old Town Academy presents an unsound educational program for the pupils to be enrolled in the charter school, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(1), based on the school’s failure to appropriately serve its special education student population.

 

From 2012-13 to 2014-15, the school’s special education student population decreased by approximately 60 percent, dropping from 23 students to just 9 students, while total enrollment grew.  Concerns regarding the significant decreases in special education student enrollment were discussed multiple times with the executive director and board chair. 

 

Of continuing concern to the district is the language on page 21 of the charter renewal petition.  It reads, “…if the student’s needs as documented on the IEP require a program other than inclusion, the school will work with the El Dorado County Charter SELPA to provide an appropriate placement and services.”  To appropriately serve the special education student population, the school must be able to accommodate students who require services other than full inclusion.

 

On page 20 of the renewal petition, it states, “[a] change in LEA status or SELPA membership shall not require a material revision of this charter.”  This statement is contrary to the district’s current practice and is unacceptable.  Charter schools are required to incorporate special education services as an integral part of the education program.  A change in LEA status or SELPA membership is a significant change that would require a material revision to a charter.

 

Finding 5:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter because the school is unfamiliar with the content of the petition as it relates to enrollment preferences, student fees, corporation status, closure procedures, and number of schools.

 

Inconsistencies and non-compliance are found in the charter petition. 

 

For example, page 16 of the renewal petition indicates that Old Town Academy has the following enrollment preferences in its policy:

  1. Students returning from the previous year
  2. Siblings of currently enrolled students
  3. Children of Old Town Academy faculty (not to exceed 10 percent of the population)
  4. Residents of areas served by the San Diego Unified School District
  5. Other California residents.

However, on page 74, in the “Element H: Admission Requirements” section, the renewal petition indicates that Old Town Academy has the following enrollment preferences in its policy:

  1. Students returning from the previous year
  2. Siblings of currently enrolled students
  3. Children of Old Town Academy faculty (not to exceed 10 percent of the population)
  4. Pupils who reside or are enrolled in the elementary school attendance area where the charter school site is located AND in which 55 percent or more of the pupil enrollment is eligible for free or reduced-price meals
  5. Residents of areas served by the San Diego Unified School District
  6. Other California residents

On page 41 of the renewal petition, as part of the summary of the three key elements of the Old Town Academy Educational Program, it states that the school offers optional after-school courses that are “fee-based but supported by a scholarship program so they are open to all.”  The course offerings include yearbook, Spanish, musical performance, studio art history, and future courses may include drama, speech and debate, ASB/student leadership, and sports programs.  Education Code section 49011 states that a pupil enrolled in a public school shall not be required to pay a pupil fee for participation in an educational activity.  Education activities are those that constitute an integral, fundamental part of elementary and secondary education, including, but not limited to, curricular and extracurricular activities.  There is no indication in the renewal petition that a third party vendor is offering the courses, so it appears that the school is charging for the courses, potentially violating the State Constitution and California Education Code.

 

The petitioners seem unclear about the corporate status of Old Town Academy and/or Tri Valley.  Page 62 of the renewal petition states that Tri Valley is formed as a California non-profit public benefit corporation pursuant to California law and has had its 501(c)(3) status recognized by the Internal Revenue Service.  On page 87 of the renewal petition it indicates that Old Town Academy “is operated by a non-profit public benefit corporation,” but then states that “it will not be if we merge.”  Petitioners have not indicated to what the corporate status will convert.

 

On page 72 of the renewal petition, incorporated into Element G (means to achieve racial/ethnic balance), Old Town Academy has indicated that “[t]he new charter school” will be right on the border of San Diego Unified District’s Region D.  Old Town Academy has not indicated to the district that they intend to operate another school site, so this language in the renewal petition is confusing.

 

Finding 6:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter because the school, despite repeated requests and letters from its authorizer, and a resolution passed by the Old Town Academy board in July 2015, has continued to authorize Tri Valley to make financial and operational decisions for the school.

 

The district is very concerned that Tri Valley continues to represent itself as the operator of Old Town Academy, without the approval of the district. 

 

In an “Assurances” document signed on August 27, 2015, and sent to the El Dorado County Charter SELPA, Tri Valley certified that its plan had been “adopted by the appropriate local board(s) (district/county) and is the basis for the operation and administration of special education programs.”  Old Town Academy was included as one of the schools in this plan, even though the district has not approved or acknowledged Tri Valley’s connection to Old Town Academy.

 

Similarly, on October 26, 2015, the district received an updated insurance certificate on behalf of Old Town Academy that listed Tri Valley and a Livermore address as the “insured” rather than Old Town Academy and the local San Diego address.

 

Finding 7:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter because Tri Valley’s past history of involvement with charter schools has been unsuccessful, and a Tri Valley board member’s past history of involvement with charter schools has been unsuccessful.

It has been reported that a current member of the Tri Valley board is also currently the Deputy Superintendent of Schools for the New Jerusalem Elementary School District (New Jerusalem).  New Jerusalem is the authorizer of two charter schools, Acacia Elementary and Acacia Middle, both of which are operated by Tri Valley.  The Deputy Superintendent of school district simultaneously serves on the charter board.  It has been reported that this same individual has had an unsuccessful history with charter schools, as summarized below:

Finding 8:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program, pursuant to Education Code section 47605(b)(2), as set forth in its charter because there is confusion about if/when the Tri Valley CEO, Bill Batchelor, left the organization, and his concerning practice of co-locating a private school with a charter school under Tri Valley’s control.

 

The Memorandum of Understanding between Tri Valley and Old Town Academy included in the renewal documents was signed on August 2, 2014, by Bill Batchelor, the CEO of Tri Valley at that time. 

 

However, the Asset Purchase Agreement included in the renewal documents has an electronic signature on August 2, 2014, indicating that John Zukoski was the acting CEO on that date. 

 

With both documents having the same date, but different people, it is unclear who was/is running Tri Valley, and when/if the leadership change occurred.

 

It has been reported that Bill Batchelor resigned from Tri Valley as CEO; however, Mr. Batchelor remains the agent for service of process.  Moreover, it is troubling that Mr. Zukoski is the acting CEO for Tri Valley because he participated in the district’s interview of the Old Town Academy administration on May 7, 2015, during which the district clarified and confirmed that Tri Valley was in fact operating only a third-party vendor capacity to the school (when conducting site visit interviews, the district confirms that if any third-party vendors are present, it is required that an actual charter school administrator is also present).  Tri Valley asserts that it was under the impression that Old Town Academy had informed the district and been approved to have Tri Valley be the operator of school in summer 2014, and yet, Mr. Zukoski as late as May 2015, represented the contrary to the district.

 

It has been reported that while Bill Batchelor was the CEO of Tri Valley, he was also serving on the Board of Directors for the San Francisco Bay Preparatory Academy (SFBPA), an international, private high school that intends to charge annual tuition for foreign students, and was the CEO of California Preparatory Academies, a “not-for-profit international private school.”  At least one of the private schools is co-located on the campus of Livermore Valley Charter Preparatory School, a charter school operated by Tri Valley.  It has been confirmed that Tri Valley charges tuition for foreign exchange students to fill seats at the Livermore charter school.

 

The district is further concerned about the growth-related and recruitment activities of Tri Valley.  In a video which can be viewed on YouTube, Mr. Batchelor, who introduces himself as the CEO of Tri Valley Learning Corporation and CEO of California Preparatory Academies, is seen attempting to sell EB5 charter school bonds to Chinese investors.  He states that Tri Valley intends to expand to seven schools by “acquiring” two schools and “expanding” two schools, and that any EB5 investors are guaranteed enrollment at the schools.  In response to questions about how the deals would be structured, Mr. Batchelor responds that the real estate is used as collateral, along with the cash flow from State government tuition and paid tuition by private students.  If Old Town Academy becomes a Tri Valley school there is nothing that prevents Tri Valley from expanding this growth and recruitment model into Old Town Academy.  It has already been reported that Tri Valley is considering operating another K-8 school and a high school in San Diego.

 

Finding 9:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school has presented an unrealistic financial plan by relinquishing financial control of the school to Tri Valley, an organization that is reported to have unpaid invoices totaling over $200,000 to a community college.

 

It has been reported that Tri Valley has, as of October 6, 2015, unpaid obligations to Las Positas Community College.  Tri Valley had an agreement with the college wherein the college would provide educational services to Tri Valley charter school students.  From spring 2013 through fall 2015, the college provided services for the charter school.  The unpaid invoices total approximately $208,554.  When the authorizer of the charter schools involved in the agreement inquired about the outstanding invoices and requested written verification that the invoices had been paid, Tri Valley responded that the issue “should be of no concern” to the authorizer.

 

The renewal petition indicates Tri Valley will control the operations of the school, including financial decisions.  The risk for Old Town Academy is that the funds generated by the school will be transferred to Tri Valley, and may not be used exclusively to support Old Town Academy.  The district is only able to conduct oversight of charter schools it has authorized.  The district has not authorized Tri Valley or any of the other charter schools that Tri Valley operates.  The concern is that the district may no longer be able to monitor the school’s fiscal condition because Tri Valley is not required to provide the district with documentation regarding the finances and operations of the entire organization.  Confirming this concern is language contained in a recent letter from Tri Valley to an authorizing district, in which Tri Valley states that an unpaid debt to a third party vendor “should be of no concern” to the authorizing district.

 

The district is concerned with the disposition of assets upon closure as stated in the renewal petition.  Page 86 of the renewal petition states, “On closure of OTA, all assets of the Charter School, including but not limited to all leaseholds, personal property, intellectual property and all ADA apportionments and other revenues generated by students attending OTA, remain the sole property of the TVLC….” 

 

If Old Town Academy were to close, the ADA generated by students attending the school and other funds will go to Tri Valley, which does not operate any charter schools in San Diego. 

 

Adding to this concern is the extent to which Tri Valley has used bonds to purchase/finance its current and future school sites.  It has been reported that the California School Finance Authority Educational Facilities Revenue Bonds (Tri-Valley Learning Corporation Project), Series 2012A for $27.5 million has been issued by the California School Finance Authority (the Authority) on October 1, 2012 as a “Limited Offering.”  The Authority will loan the proceeds of the Bonds to Livermore Valley Charter School and Livermore Valley Charter Preparatory High School, both operated by Tri-Valley Learning Corporation, a California nonprofit public benefit corporation (the Borrower) pursuant to a Loan Agreement, dated as of October 1, 2012, by and between the Authority and the Borrower (the Loan Agreement).  The funds will “finance the acquisition, construction, improvement, and equipping of certain education facilities…to be used or operated by the Borrower.…”  The schedule of loan repayments included in the Loan Agreement indicates variable annual payments, with the average annual payment over the 2015-16 to 2020-12 period being $1.752 million.

 

In May 2015, a tax-exempt revenue bond (the obligation”), not to exceed $30 million, was approved by the California Statewide Communities Development Authority, for “educational facilities to be owned by Independence Support, LLC, and initially leased to Tri-Valley Learning Corporation and California Preparatory Academies for the purposes of (1) financing the acquisition, construction, renovation, improvement, and equipping of public charter school and private school facilities…located at 3090 Independence Drive, Livermore, California 94551….”  Livermore Charter Zone Corporation is the sole member of Independence Support.  According to the California Secretary of State website, the agent for service of process for Livermore Charter Zone Corporation and California Preparatory Academies is Bill Batchelor, the “former” CEO of Tri Valley, and the agent for service of process for Independence Support is Derek L. Austin.  Mr. Austin is the general counsel for Tri Valley.  It has been reported that the lease payments made by Tri Valley and California Preparatory Academies to Independence Support are a more than $1 million annually, and come from the money that the charter school generates in State ADA funds, as well as the private school’s tuition.

 

According to the Ed-Data website, during the 2014-15 school year, the four schools operated by Tri Valley had a combined total enrollment of approximately 1,869 students.  With this low number of charter school students, potentially $57 million in combined debt, and annual payments around $2.75 million, there is a risk that Tri Valley may become indebted to a point where funds are no longer available to support the educational programs, or that funds generated by Old Town Academy will be diverted to help pay Tri Valley’s outstanding loans.

 

Tri Valley has asserted that it “has no obligation” in the $30 million bond transaction, but the documents for the bond indicate Tri Valley is leasing the property, and therefore would have some obligations for the payments.  Charter schools operated by Tri Valley and repaying the loan would also be obligated and affected in the event that the payments are not made.  Tri Valley has at least its two Livermore charter schools housed in buildings that were bought or funded with bond money.  It is unlikely that those schools would be allowed to stay at these sites, and Old Town Academy, as a school of Tri Valley, would be impacted if the payments were not made.

 

The district has a significant concern with the manner in which Old Town Academy, a public school, appears to have been “sold” to a private corporation.  Without notification to, or approval from the authorizer, Old Town Academy entered into several agreements with Tri Valley whereby the assets, liabilities, and operations of Old Town Academy were transferred to Tri Valley.  Below is a summary of the documents used to “sell” this public school.

  • A Bill of Sale dated July 1, 2015, indicating that “for good and valuable consideration” (the consideration is not specified in the Bill of Sale) Old Town Academy does “hereby sell, convey, assign, transfer and deliver” to Tri Valley, all of Old Town Academy’s “right, title and interest in and to the Assets” (as that term is defined in the Asset Purchase Agreement).
  • A Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) between Tri Valley and Old Town Academy that establishes and delineates “the relationship between the Corporation and the School as it relates to the operations and management of the School(s).”  This MOU also contemplates additional school(s) or site(s).  It references the “expansion and creation of other School satellite sites” and states that “Additional School locations not in geographic competition with the School’s existing facility shall be at the Corporation’s discretion and does not require School site council approval.”  There is no mention of authorizer approval for these expansions within the MOU.
  • An Asset Purchase Agreement entered into August 2, 2014, that transfers $226,500 worth of Old town Academy’s supplies and equipment (ipads, tables, desks, computers, textbooks, etc.) to Tri Valley.  The purchase price listed in the Asset Purchase Agreement states that “Seller and Buyer agree that consideration for the purchase was received by Seller in the form of services rendered by Buyer to Seller, and Buyer’s assumption of liabilities as set forth herein.”  It should be noted that the Asset Purchase Agreement has a closing date effective August 2, 2014, but the Inventory of Supplies and Equipment included as part of the Agreement has a date of September 7, 2015, a full year after the closing.
  • An Assignment and Assumption Agreement dated August 2, 2014, that indicates that Old Town Academy has assigned to Tri Valley “all of its respective right, title and interest, if any, in and to the Lease and Contracts as described in Exhibit A.”  Exhibit A references a lease between Old Town Academy (as tenant) and “PV Old Town, LLC” (as landlord), and any “obligations under that certain Charter from authorizer SDUSD, as may be amended and/or renewed to provide for TVLC to be the operator thereunder.”

The district believes that local public charter schools that it has authorized cannot simply be “sold” to an out-of-town corporation.  Similarly, a charter school authorized by San Diego Unified School District cannot change its financial, operational, and governance components without seeking, at a minimum, a approval for the proposed material revision prior to the requested changes.  The documents used in the transaction may transfer certain properties, but they cannot and should not be used as a way of “selling” an entire public school.

 

Finding 10:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school has presented a vague and unclear administrative services plan.

 

The charter and supporting documents do not adequately describe the structure for providing administrative services for Old Town Academy.  It is not clear what services will be provided by Old Town Academy employees and what services will be provided through contracted services.  There are no detailed descriptions of any services that are provided for the school. 

 

Finding 11:  Old Town Academy is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program as set forth in its charter because the school has presented a vague and unclear budget and cash flow that is inconsistent, inaccurate, and possibly a misrepresentation.

 

The budget submitted with the renewal petition only includes budget assumptions for ADA, per pupil property tax rate, and per pupil lottery rates.  No assumptions for expenses can be determined by analyzing the limited budget information that the school has provided.  For example, there are no assumptions provided to substantiate the reasonableness of salary costs budgeted and projected.  In addition, the budget does not differentiate between unrestricted and restricted revenues and expenditures.

 

The renewal petition does not contain a detailed budget showing the breakdown of revenues and expenditures.  For example, in the revenues section it lists “All Other State Revenue” with a projected annual amount.  There is no information regarding what has been included in this category (such as special education entitlement, child nutrition, school facilities apportionments, state lottery revenue, etc.).  The same is true in the expenses section.  There is a category listed as “Personnel – Dedicated” with a projected annual amount.  There is no information as to whether these are certificated employees, classified employees, part-time or full-time employees, and whether employee benefits are included as they are not included anywhere else in the budget.  Similarly, there is no breakdown under the “Services and Other Operating Expenses” category.   The documents are lacking detail such that the district is unable to determine if the budget and projected cash flow statements are sound, and if the estimates of expenditures are reasonable. 

 

Old Town Academy is a member of the El Dorado SELPA, and as such receives federal (IDEA Basic Local Assistance Entitlement, Part B, Section 611) and state (Special Education AB 602 Apportionment) funding as a pass through of revenue from El Dorado SELPA.  The budget does not project federal funding of any kind.  As indicated above, the “All Other State Revenue” category does not contain sufficient details such that the district is unable to determine if Special Education AB 602 Apportionment is included in the budget.

 

All other local revenue is projected at $100,000 for fiscal years 2016-17 through 2022-23; however, there is no description as to the source of the revenue.

 

The budget included in the renewal petition does not appear to disclose important financial details related to Tri Valley.  The budget includes no oversight and/or administrative fees being paid to Tri Valley from Old Town Academy.  Most management organizations providing services to charter schools have a percentage or other fee structure wherein fees are paid from the individual schools to the management organization.  The Old Town Academy budget does not disclose any such fees.  The district has the understanding, based on discussions during Tri Valley’s September 24, 2015, board meeting, that the other charter schools operated by Tri Valley pay a fee to Tri Valley.  The district is concerned that there is a fee being paid to Tri Valley by Old Town Academy that is not being disclosed in the renewal petition.

 

Old Town Academy’s enrollment projection is optimistic. According to the petition, the school is projecting enrollment of 270 students for the 2016-17 fiscal year, which would be a gain of 7.14 percent from the prior year of 252 students.  Over the past three years, Old Town Academy’s enrollment has grown an average of less than 1 percent from the prior year.

 

If Old Town Academy does not attain its full enrollment projection in fiscal year 2016-17, the SB740, special education, and LCFF revenue projections are overestimated, which will result in net operating losses in fiscal years 2016-2017 through 2022-23.

Included in the renewal documents submitted by Old Town Academy is the California Department of Education’s 2013-14 School Quality Snapshot.  This document confirms that Old Town Academy met its schoolwide growth target.  The school’s only numerically significant subgroup (White) also met its growth target.

Academic achievement is the most important factor in a charter school’s renewal; however, the district cannot overlook significant decreases in a specific group of students within the school.

 

CONCLUSION

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operation in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement if any.

 

Academic achievement, while the most important factor for a charter’s renewal, does not override, replace, or negate the other required elements of a charter petition.  As detailed in the above findings, the renewal petition presents significant operational and financial concerns.

 

Staff recommends the board deny the request to renew the charter of Old Town Academy and adopt the above-identified findings.
