BACKGROUND: Audeo Charter School (Audeo) is seeking a renewal of its charter.  Audeo, along with Charter School of San Diego and Laurel Preparatory Academy (Laurel) are described as being part of the “Altus” network.  Altus is a private corporation.  The public hearing to consider the level of support for Audeo was held on November 3, 2015.

 

The board has the following options regarding the renewal of Audeo Charter School:

 

Option 1: Deny the renewal of the charter and adopt the below Findings in support of the denial.

 

Option 2: Grant the renewal of the charter as submitted, including all seventeen in-district and out-of-district sites described in the documents.

 

Option 3: Grant the renewal of the charter as to the seven sites (Kearny Mesa Resource Center, Hazard Center Resource Center, Pacific Beach Resource Center, Sorrento Mesa Administrative Office, Old Town Administrative Office, La Jolla Resource Center, and Moreno Valley Resource Center) that comply with the geographic limitations of the law, and direct staff to continue to collaborate with Audeo in an effort to ensure a smooth transition with remaining sites, as well as the clarifications specified below in this analysis. 

 

Staff recommends Option 3, such that the board grants the renewal of the Audeo Charter School and Special Education Agreement for five-year terms beginning July 1, 2016, and ending June 30, 2021, to serve Grades K-12, for the seven sites that comply with the geographical limitations of the law, as well as the clarifications specified below in this analysis.

 

Note, all references to page numbers within the Audeo charter petition renewal documents reflect the number located on the upper right hand side of the attached 530-page PDF document.

 

FINDINGS

 

Finding 1: The attached charter petition documents submitted by Audeo do not contain a reasonably comprehensive description of the school’s governance structure because the information presented is vague and unclear.

 

Audeo’s governance structure is vague and unclear because the organizational and technical design allows for the following financial agreements and practices to be in place with Altus:

  • Audeo, through its governance structure and financial agreements with Altus, a private corporation, appears to be paying fees to “itself” for board members and employees that overlap with Altus and Charter School of San Diego.  Charter employees who are also charter board members can receive full-time financial compensation at one charter school, while receiving additional financial compensation for providing “on-loan” services to the other charter schools. 

    --For example, Mary Searcy Bixby is a board member of Altus, Audeo, Charter School of San Diego, and Laurel.  Ms. Bixby is a full-time employee of the Charter School of San Diego, while she is also “on-loan” to Altus to provide services to Audeo and Laurel.  In addition to her compensation as an employee of Charter School of San Diego, through a “Master Agreement for Personnel Services,” Ms. Bixby agreed to accept $2,450 $3,000 per month. for each additional school (Audeo and Laurel) to which she is assigned to provide services.  According to the website http://www.altusinstitute.net/educational-reform-project/, Ms. Bixby is identified as the Founder, President & CEO of Altus and the Charter School of San Diego.  This is analogous to an individual simultaneously being a school board member, the district superintendent, and “on-loan” to the schools.  (See attached Employment Agreements re Bixby and Alipio.)

    --In another example, Lynne Alipio, is an employee of the Charter School of San Diego, while being “on-loan” to Altus to provide services to Audeo and Laurel.  In addition to her compensation as the Chief Business Officer of Charter School of San Diego, through a “Master Agreement for Personnel Services,” Ms. Alipio agreed to accept $2,450 per month. for each additional school (Audeo and Laurel) to which she is assigned to provide services.  (See attached Employment Agreements re Bixby and Alipio.)
  • Audeo pays Altus $21,000 annually in fees for advocacy, outreach, school reform services and periodic reports through an Agreement for Advocacy Services. Charter School of San Diego pays Altus $64,000 in annual fees.  (See attached Service Agreement with Altus.)
  • In addition to the $21,000 annual fee, Audeo pays Altus a $4,159 monthly “Base Fee” plus an additional $120 “per ADA Fee” through a Memorandum of Understanding for Programmatic Support Services, Advisory Support, and Supervisorial Oversight; Evaluation of the Education Program and Student Achievement Accountability; Business Services; Financial Services, Fiscal Controls, and Accountability; and, Professional Development.  (See attached MOUs with Altus.
  • Audeo’s governance structure allows for a single individual, Ms. Bixby, to be delegated full authority to make any and all real estate transactions, personnel decisions, etc. without any agendized items to have these actions presented, reviewed, and approved by the Audeo board.  As a result, the Audeo board has not met in closed session for any topic for at least the past three years.  The district’s concern is that a single individual, rather than a board that meets and reports its actions in open public meetings, has decision-making authority over a public charter school’s operations. 

Page 86 of the charter states that Audeo is an “independent” charter school that is governed by its own board; however, all of the Altus board members are also Audeo board members.  Table 7 below summarizes the overlapping board members:

Finding 2: Audeo is demonstrably unlikely to successfully implement the program with regard to its financial and operational plan because the buildings purchased with public funds for Charter School of San Diego have been transferred to Altus. 

 

Page 140 of the Audeo charter identifies two sites (10170 Huennekens Street and 3252 Bonita Road) that have been purchased with funds belonging the Charter School of San Diego.  Audeo, Charter School of San Diego, and Laurel are three different charter schools, operated by separate boards of separate corporations.  Each school receives public school funds based on their respective average daily attendance (ADA).

 

Charter School of San Diego purchased the buildings at Huennekens Street and Bonita Road using $8,028,074 of public school funds.  Charter School of San Diego then transferred legal ownership of $8 million worth of buildings to Altus.  Because Altus is not authorized by the district, there is no oversight between the district and Altus.

 

Lynn Alipio, Chief Business Officer, stated on August 27, 2015, “Although Altus Institute holds the legal title as the Trustee of the properties for the benefit of The Charter School of San Diego, Altus must operate and maintain the property for The Charter School of San Diego, and cannot use, convey, or otherwise transfer, pledge or encumber the property for any other purpose. The Charter School of San Diego has continued to utilize the real property in the same manner as prior to the transfer with no loss of rights or usage.” It is unrealistic to believe Altus is maintaining the property solely for the use of Charter School of San Diego based on the fact that Audeo has identified this address as one of its sites in its charter. 

 

Since the Charter School of San Diego purchased buildings with public school funds, it is unclear why these buildings were transferred to Altus, a private corporation.  It is unclear why these building are not being used to provide instruction to the students of Charter School of San Diego, and instead are being used by Audeo as administrative offices, as well as Laurel.  These three charter schools are not interchangeable; rather, these charter schools have been presented as distinct, separate legal entities with separate boards that must compensate each other for the services of “on-loan” employees.

Pages 138-141 of the charter identify ten sites that do not comply with the Charter Schools Act. 

 

The Barrio Logan Resource Center, Navajo Resource Center, and South Park Resource Center as described on page 139 of the Audeo charter renewal documents, fall outside the district’s charter granting authority at this time because Audeo has not included address information. 

 

The Westminster Resource Center, Carlsbad Annex Resource Center, Carlsbad Resource Center, Escondido Resource Center, San Marcos Resource Center, and Bonita Training Center locations as described on pages 139-140 of the Audeo charter renewal documents fall outside the district’s charter granting authority at this time because they are not located within the district.

 

The Mission Valley Resource Center at 3420 and 3430 Camino Del Rio North, San Diego 92108, falls outside the district’s charter granting authority at this time based on ongoing negotiations regarding the terms of the facilities agreement between Audeo and the district.

  1. Approve One Resource Center in an Adjacent County.

Under the charter granting authority set forth by Education Code section 47605.1(c), staff recommends the board approve Audeo to operate the Moreno Valley Resource Center, which is located in Riverside County, adjacent to San Diego County:

  • Moreno Valley Resource Center, 27130 Eucalyptus Avenue, Suite A, Moreno Valley 92555

Legal Authority: Education Code section 47605.1(c) states, “Notwithstanding any other provision, a charter school may establish a resource center, meeting space, or other satellite facility located in a county adjacent to that in which the charter school is authorized if the following conditions are met: (1) The facility is used exclusively for the educational support of pupils who are enrolled in non-classroom based independent study of the charter school. (2) The charter school provides its primary educational services in, and a majority of the pupils it serves are residents of, the county in which the school is authorized.”

 

The other proposed sites identified in the Audeo charter petition documents fall outside the authority of the district to grant at this time.  

 

The Barrio Logan Resource Center, Navajo Resource Center, and South Park Resource Center as described on page 139 of the Audeo charter renewal documents, fall outside the district’s charter granting authority at this time because Audeo has not included address information. 

 

The Moreno Valley Resource Center, Carlsbad Annex Resource Center, Carlsbad Resource Center, Escondido Resource Center, San Marcos Resource Center, and Bonita Training Center locations as described on pages 139-140 of the Audeo charter renewal documents fall outside the district’s charter granting authority at this time because they are not located within the district.  The following recent actions by the Audeo board are also noted:

  • On September 24, 2015, the Audeo board voted to “transfer” the Westminster Resource Center to Mirus Charter School.  Hesperia Unified School District is the charter granting authority of the Mirus Charter School. 
  • On October 30, 2015, the Audeo board voted to approve submitting a charter petition to Carlsbad Unified School District.  If this charter petition is approved by Carlsbad Unified School District as the charter granting authority, the Carlsbad Annex Resource Center and Carlsbad Resource Center would become in compliance with the law.

The Mission Valley Resource Center at 3420 and 3430 Camino Del Rio North, San Diego 92108, fall outside the district’s charter granting authority at this time based on ongoing negotiations regarding the terms of the facilities agreement between Audeo and the district.  Once the terms of the facilities agreement have been finalized, Audeo may complete the attached “Charter Revision Form” for consideration of the board, at a future date to approve this location, as well as any other changes in locations.

 

Legal Authority: Education Code section 47605(a)(4) states, "After receiving approval of its petition, a charter school that proposes to establish one or more additional sites shall request a material revision to its charter and shall notify the authority that granted its charter of those additional locations.  The authority that granted its charter shall consider whether to approve those additional locations at an open, public meeting.”

 

The district notes that Audeo submitted a “Transition Plan” as part of its charter petition renewal documents in order “to bring Audeo’s facilities into compliance” with the charter granting authority’s understanding of applicable law. 

  1. Approve Audeo Board as the Decision-Making Body in Charter School’s Governance Structure.

Under the charter granting authority set forth by Education Code sections 47604 and 47605, staff recommends the board grant Audeo’s charter renewal with the district’s express understanding that the Audeo board is the only decision-making body for all of Audeo’s operations, including, but not limited to, approving the Audeo board and the disposition of all of Audeo’s assets.  The district’s charter granting authority does not allow oversight or approval of a governance structure that allows the private entity Altus to “veto” the decisions of the public school Audeo.  Consequently, any and all references in the charter, including the bylaws at page 449 describing Altus as the “sole statutory member” of Audeo is denied as falling outside the district’s charter granting authority.  

 

Legal Authority: Education Code section 47604(a) states, “Charter schools may elect to operate as, or be operated by, a nonprofit public benefit corporation, formed and organized pursuant to the Nonprofit Public Benefit Corporation Law (Part 2 commencing with Section 5110) of Division 2 of Title 1 of the Corporation Code.”

 

On November 2, 2015, Audeo submitted a letter to the district that states, “The right of the sole statutory member under the Corporations Code (Sec. 5056) only allows the statutory member the right to veto a vote of the Audeo board to dispose of all or substantially all of Audeo’s assets – it does not give Altus the right to initiate that decision.  Therefore, all decision making impacting Audeo is performed by the Audeo Board which is subject to the oversight of the district.”  This statement is nonsensical.  There is no legitimate reason for the private corporation Altus to have “veto power” or any other authority over the public charter school Audeo. 

 

Further, to ensure parental involvement with respect to access to the Audeo board, staff recommends the board grant the renewal with the district’s express understanding that all Audeo board meetings be held within the boundaries of the district. 

 

Legal Authority: Education Code section 47605(b)(5)(D) requires a charter petition to contain a reasonably comprehensive description of the governance structure of the school, including, but not limited to, the process to be followed by the school to ensure parental involvement.
  1. Approve Dispute Resolution Procedures with Clarifications:

Under the charter granting authority set forth by Education Code section 47605, staff recommends the board grant Audeo’s charter renewal with following clarifications noted on page 131 of the Audeo charter petition renewal documents:

 

In the event of a dispute between Audeo Charter School and the district regarding the terms of this charter or any other issue regarding the Charter School and the District’s relationship, Audeo Charter School staff, employees and Board members and the district agree to first frame the issue in written format (dispute statement) and to refer the issue to the District Superintendent or designee and the Audeo Charter School Coordinator. In the event that the district Board of Education believes that the dispute relates to an issue that could lead to revocation of the charter in accordance with Education Code Section 47607, Audeo Charter School requests that this shall be noted in the written dispute statement, although it recognizes it cannot legally bind the district to do so.  However, participation in the dispute resolution procedures outlined in this section shall not be interpreted to impede or act as a pre-requisite to the district’s ability to proceed with revocation in accordance with Education Code Section 47607.

 

The Audeo Charter School Coordinator or designee and District Superintendent or designee shall informally meet and confer in a timely fashion to attempt to resolve the dispute, not later than five (5) business days at the earliest mutually convenient date from receipt of the dispute statement.  In the event that this informal meeting fails to resolve the dispute, both parties shall identify two Board members from their respective boards two representatives from their respective organizations who shall jointly meet with the District Superintendent or designee and the School Coordinator at the earliest mutually convenient date and attempt to resolve the dispute within fifteen (15) business days from receipt of the dispute statement.

 

If this joint meeting fails to resolve the dispute, the District Superintendent and School Coordinator or their designees shall meet to jointly identify a neutral third party mediator to engage the parties in a mediation session designed to facilitate resolution of the dispute. The format of the mediation session shall be developed jointly by the District Superintendent or designee and the School Coordinator. Mediation shall be held within sixty (60) business days of receipt of the dispute statement at the earliest mutually convenient date. The costs of the mediator shall be split equally between the district and Audeo Charter School. Audeo Charter School shall be solely responsible for its attorney’s fees, if any, and any other costs or expenses arising from a dispute.  If mediation does not resolve the dispute either party may pursue any other remedy available under the law. All timelines and procedures in this section may be revised upon mutual written agreement of the District and Audeo Charter School.

 

Legal Authority: Education Code section 47605(b)(5)(N) requires a charter petition to contain a reasonably comprehensive description of the procedures to be followed by the charter school and the entity granting the charter to resolves disputes relating to provisions of the charter.

Any assets transferred from Audeo to Altus shall be returned if required by law or funded with public monies.

RENEWALS

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement if any.

 

Staff has visited Audeo annually. The annual site visit includes document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board member(s), teacher(s), administrator(s), financial manager(s), parent(s), and/or student(s). During the annual site visit, as well as throughout the year, the areas of academics, finances, and operations are monitored as part of the district’s oversight duties.

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

ACADEMICS

 

A charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school. 
  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years. 
  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.  
  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.  
  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).

Assembly Bill (AB) 484 amended Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 and 2014–15 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  1. The most recent API calculation;
  2. An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or
  3. An alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups. 

The decision to use one of these criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

 

The district has considered increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by Audeo as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.  As detailed in the tables below, Audeo has attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in 2011-12 and 2012-13, thereby meeting the eligibility requirements for renewal.

Audeo participates in the Alternative Schools Accountability Model (ASAM).  As an ASAM school, Audeo does not receive API ranks and is no longer required to collect and report data to the California Department of Education on ASAM performance measures as required in previous years. 

 

OPERATIONS

 

Audeo Charter School is operated by a nonprofit public benefit corporation by the same name.  Audeo operates what it describes as a non-classroom based independent study program for students in Grades K-12.  Classroom instruction is included as part of the program. 

 

Audeo is a member of the El Dorado County Charter Special Education Local Plan Area (SELPA) and has maintained comparable enrollment total with regard to students who are eligible to receive special education and related services.

 

The Uniform Complaint Policy for Audeo is included in the charter renewal documents as Appendix Y.

 

The district has communicated to Audeo that the charter school’s desire to operate sites located in multiple districts throughout San Diego County appears to better align with Education Code section 47605.6 which expressly permits a county board of education to approve a petition for the operation of a charter school that operates at one or more sites within the geographic boundaries of the county.

 

Further, the district has communicated to Audeo that the school’s desire to operate sites located in multiple counties throughout California appears to better align with Education Code section 47605.8 for a statewide benefit charter.

 

The governance structure of Audeo is detailed above under the Findings section.

 

FINANCES

 

Audeo offers eligible employees to participate in California State Teachers’ Retirement System (CalSTRS) and California Public Employees' Retirement System (CalPERS).

 

Based on the budget and cash flow information submitted in the charter petition renewal documents, Audeo has been found to be financially viable.

 

In addition, the district has examined whether Audeo maintains an adequate Reserve for Economic Uncertainty greater than 3 percent of expenses or $50,000, whichever is greater, as another consideration.  At the end of the fiscal year 2014-15, per Audeo’s unaudited report, the ending fund balance (EFB) of $5,563,389.18 exceeded the reserve requirement. 

 

In summary, Audeo appears financially sound.

RECOMMENDATION:  Grant the revision of the governance portions of the charter, effective January 1, 2016, of Elevate Elementary to reduce the number of parent board members from three to two and, in the event a parent board seat is vacated, allow the Elevate Elementary board to appoint another parent to complete the remainder of the term.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  Staff recommends the board grant the revision of the governance portions of the charter of Elevate Elementary to reduce the number of parent board members from three to two and, in the event a parent board seat is vacated, allow the Elevate Elementary board to appoint another parent to complete the remainder of the term.

 

Elevate Elementary is a charter school serving approximately 213 students in Grades K-5, at a non-district site located at 2285 Murray Ridge Road, San Diego, 92123, which is in the Kearny High cluster.  The charter was approved by the board on December 10, 2013, for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2014, and ending June 30, 2019.

 

The charter, including the bylaws, of Elevate Elementary currently provides that the school will be governed by a charter board comprised of five to eleven voting members, of which three parent representatives will be elected amongst the parent body (one vote per family) and two community representatives will be appointed by the charter board.

 

Elevate Elementary reports that many of its students are children of one or more parents who are serving in the military.  These families may experience more frequent mobility due to deployments and/or permanent change of station (PCS) orders, which may result in board vacancies prior to the end of the designated term.  In order to maintain board membership consistency, Elevate Elementary has proposed the following changes to its bylaws:

  • Reduce the number of parent representatives on the charter board from three to two members.
  • In the event a parent representative seat is vacated, the charter board will appoint another parent to that position to complete the remainder of the term, rather than be elected amongst the parent body.

RECOMMENDATION:  Deny revision of the charter of Keiller Leadership Academy to add Grades 9-12 based on the following findings:

  • The school’s financial and operational plans contain significant internal inconsistencies and discrepancies, including the projected enrollment totals.
  • The school’s financial and operational plans contain an unrealistic retention rate of 100 percent.
  • The physical limitation of the 7.5-acre campus that Keiller proposes to house Grades 9-12 does not support the significant increase in population and use, including, but not limited to traffic and parking, proposed by the school.

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  Staff recommends the board deny the request to revise the charter of Keiller Leadership Academy to serve Grades 9-12.

 

Keiller Leadership Academy (Keiller) is a charter school that is operated by a nonprofit public benefit corporation by the same name. Keiller is located at a district site at 7270 Lisbon Street, San Diego, 92114, which is located in the Morse High cluster. 

 

Keiller originally served middle school grades.  After experiencing enrollment declines from 500+ students in 2006 to fewer than 400 students in 2011, Keiller was approved to begin serving Grades K-8 in 2012.  This information is summarized below in Table 1.

With regard to facilities, the physical limitation of the 7.5-acre campus that Keiller occupies does not support the significant increase in population and use, including, but not limited to traffic and parking, proposed by the school.  Keiller is currently located at a district site on a 7.5-acre campus.  The Keiller campus is significantly smaller than other charters schools that serve a large total enrollment that includes high school grades.  For example, Gompers Preparatory Academy is located on a 32-acre campus, while O’Farrell Charter School is located on a 30-acre campus. 

 

Opening and successfully operating a high school complex is a serious endeavor that warrants a clear, realistic, and comprehensive plan. Based on the documents submitted and reviewed, staff recommends the board deny the request to revise the charter of Keiller Leadership Academy to serve Grades 9-12.
